description:
In lichen_lora_l2_deinit(), rx_callback and rx_callback_user_data are cleared without holding any mutex:

```c
/* Clear initialized flag first - this blocks any concurrent operations */
atomic_set(&lora_state.initialized, 0);

/* Clear aborted flag - module is now in clean uninitialized state */
atomic_set(&lora_state.aborted, 0);

/* Clear state - defensive, init will overwrite anyway */
lora_state.rx_callback = NULL;           // Line 509 - no mutex!
lora_state.rx_callback_user_data = NULL; // Line 510 - no mutex!
```

While the comment says 'We do NOT acquire lora_mutex here' due to the aborted state potentially leaving it locked, the rx_thread reads these fields under mutex. If the thread is still terminating (join_ret == -EAGAIN path), writing these without the mutex creates a data race.

Impact: P2 - potential data race during recovery path. In practice, the initialized flag being cleared should prevent the RX thread from invoking the callback, but the write itself is technically racy.
